==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Snuffle
<hw>Snuf"fle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Snuffled</conjf><pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Snuffling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Freq. of
<ets>snuff</ets>, v.i.; akin to LG. <ets>snuffeln</ets>, G.
<ets>schn⟦uum⟧ffeln</ets>, D. <ets>snuffeln</ets>, Dan.
<ets>sn⟦oum⟧vle</ets>. Cf. <er>Sniffle</er>.]</ety> <def>To speak
through the nose; to breathe through the nose when it is obstructed, so
as to make a broken sound.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One clad in purple⟦br⟧
Eats, and recites some lamentable rhyme . . . ⟦br⟧
<qex>Snuffling</qex> at nose, and croaking in his throat.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snuffle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Snuffle
<hw>Snuf"fle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of snuffing; a
sound made by the air passing through the nose when
obstructed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This dread sovereign, Breath, in its passage, gave a snort or
<qex>snuffle</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An affected nasal twang; hence, cant;
hypocrisy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>Obstruction of the nose by mucus;
nasal catarrh of infants or children.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snuffler</ent>⟦br⟧
